all of these investments

00:54:10.340 --> 00:54:13.620
by metro driven by the
sustainability ideal.

00:54:13.620 --> 00:54:18.230
And urban quality of life and
connectivity and all that.

00:54:18.230 --> 00:54:20.930
And I really appreciate
how your work

00:54:20.930 --> 00:54:23.450
grapples with some of the
tensions and contradictions

00:54:23.450 --> 00:54:24.800
inherent in that.

00:54:24.800 --> 00:54:28.640
And you spoke about displacement
of communities of color

00:54:28.640 --> 00:54:33.470
from the urban core who are the
ones predominantly taking buses

00:54:33.470 --> 00:54:36.090
and really not owning cars.

00:54:36.090 --> 00:54:38.660
And then they're getting pushed
out to these outlying areas

00:54:38.660 --> 00:54:41.060
where they're now
reliant on cars.

00:54:41.060 --> 00:54:45.440
And I wanted to
ask you if that's

00:54:45.440 --> 00:54:47.660
a deliberate thing,
where you grapple with,

00:54:47.660 --> 00:54:53.390
not just intergenerational
aspects within the characters

00:54:53.390 --> 00:54:55.730
but almost
intergenerational aspects

00:54:55.730 --> 00:54:57.620
within the cities themselves.

00:54:57.620 --> 00:55:00.710
You know how cities change
because of these new ideas

00:55:00.710 --> 00:55:04.190
and the zeitgeist in some ways.

00:55:04.190 --> 00:55:08.254
- I think one thing
that's important

00:55:08.254 --> 00:55:10.420
and that again is another
thing that I didn't really

00:55:10.420 --> 00:55:15.160
realize probably before I became
really interested in cities

00:55:15.160 --> 00:55:17.750
is to differentiate between
what it is a zeitgeist

00:55:17.750 --> 00:55:20.960
and what is the priority
and norm at the time.

00:55:20.960 --> 00:55:24.730
And where does private corporate
interests intersect in there.

00:55:24.730 --> 00:55:26.530
So some of the things
that have happened

00:55:26.530 --> 00:55:29.020
in Detroit as far as just
the way the city is laid out.

00:55:29.020 --> 00:55:31.210
It has these wide grand
avenues and everyone

00:55:31.210 --> 00:55:33.700
is spread apart from each other
because of the automobile.

00:55:33.700 --> 00:55:35.117
Because we all
wanted to have cars

00:55:35.117 --> 00:55:36.950
and that was part of
the middle class ideal.

00:55:36.950 --> 00:55:38.740
But it's also because
that was the driving

00:55:38.740 --> 00:55:39.980
industry in the city.

00:55:39.980 --> 00:55:42.760
And so they wanted everyone
to have to need a car.

00:55:42.760 --> 00:55:46.030
And similarly in LA,
you had families,

00:55:46.030 --> 00:55:50.440
you had very influential
automobile connected families

00:55:50.440 --> 00:55:55.150
that helped encourage the city
to turn their funding away

00:55:55.150 --> 00:55:58.870
from the criss-cross of street
car lines they had before

00:55:58.870 --> 00:56:02.950
and encouraged them more
to invest in infrastructure

00:56:02.950 --> 00:56:05.300
like the highway system.

00:56:05.300 --> 00:56:06.850
So it's not just--

00:56:06.850 --> 00:56:10.150
that's one thing that I
think is hard to at the time

00:56:10.150 --> 00:56:12.400
when it's happening especially
because we don't always

00:56:12.400 --> 00:56:15.250
know, at the time when it
happens it does feel like we're

00:56:15.250 --> 00:56:17.890
just all kind of galloping
forward as a culture.

00:56:17.890 --> 00:56:19.840
But there is also
sometimes someone

00:56:19.840 --> 00:56:24.550
who is the jockey, who's
kind of riding us forward

00:56:24.550 --> 00:56:28.630
and who does not necessarily
have all of the residents best

00:56:28.630 --> 00:56:29.530
interests in mind.

00:56:29.530 --> 00:56:32.344
Whether that is
certain developers who

00:56:32.344 --> 00:56:34.760
have this new parcel of land
and it's out here in Cerritos

00:56:34.760 --> 00:56:37.142
and they want people
to go live in Cerritos.

00:56:37.142 --> 00:56:39.100
And they encourage the
city to figure out a way

00:56:39.100 --> 00:56:40.810
to get people out to Cerritos.

00:56:40.810 --> 00:56:46.999
Or whether that is what does
like our bike-share system

00:56:46.999 --> 00:56:48.790
look like in a city
and who is a person who

00:56:48.790 --> 00:56:51.570
influences those decisions.

00:56:51.570 --> 00:56:53.680
And so I think it's
both things that

00:56:53.680 --> 00:56:56.650
have to be kind of explored
before we can really figure out

00:56:56.650 --> 00:56:58.720
how much of it is
just where we are

00:56:58.720 --> 00:57:01.680
and what is the
cultural influence.

